Cipla, Naspers, Hulamin, Telkom: South African Equity Preview

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a   a n d   M i k e   C o h e n
-- 
2011-03-17T06:30:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-16/evraz-gold-reef-investec-purple-south-african-equity-preview.html
The following stocks may rise or
fall in  South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last close.  South  Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index rose 418.46,
or 1.4 percent, to 30,612.41 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg.    Cipla Medpro South Africa Ltd. (CMP)  : The genetic drugs
manufacturer said net income climbed to 195.4 million rand ($28
million) for the 12 months through December, from 159.9 million
rand a year earlier. The stock advanced 19 cents, or 2.8
percent, to 7.07 rand.  Efficient Financial Holdings Ltd. (EFG SJ): The asset
management and research company said it increased net income to
2.7 million rand in the six months through February, compared
with a 1.2 million-rand profit a year earlier. The stock was
unchanged at 5.20 rand.    Evraz Highveld Steel and Vanadium Ltd. (EHS)  : The steel-
maker reported a loss per share of 5.54 rand in the year ended
December, from a profit per share of 1.64 rand a year earlier,
according to a financial statement published on the Johannesburg
bourse’s news service. Evraz was unchanged at 92 rand.    Gold Reef Resorts Ltd. (GDF)  : The casino and gaming
company publishes financial results for the year ended December.
It said on March 2 that earnings may drop by as much as 25
percent. The shares lost 13 cents, or 0.9 percent, to 15.05
rand.    Hulamin Ltd. (HLM)  : An application by Africa’s largest
aluminum processor to the nation’s International Trade
Administration Commission for a 10 percent duty on semi-
fabricated, rolled products is opposed by some members of the
Aluminium Association of South Africa, Business Day reported.
Most of the association’s members weren’t aware of the
application and didn’t have time to lodge objections, the
Johannesburg-based newspaper cited Metal & Tool Trade Managing
Director Volker Schutte, a member of Afsa, as saying. Hulamin
slipped 30 cents, or 2.7 percent, to 7.30 rand.  Investec Ltd. (INL SJ): The investment and private banking
company holds a media briefing before it enters a closed period
for the year ending March. The stock gained 1.62 rand, or 3.3,
to 51.11 rand.    Naspers Ltd. (NPN)  : Tencent Holdings Ltd.,  China ’s
biggest Internet company, fell the most in more than two years
in Hong Kong trading after President Martin Lau said earnings
growth is “certain” to slow. Naspers, Africa’s largest media
company, owns about 35 percent of Tencent. Naspers shares fell
2.30 rand, or 0.6 percent, to 382.70 rand.    Purple Capital Ltd. (PPE)  : The company with investments
in finance and asset-management businesses reported a 1.3
million-rand profit during the first half through February, from
a loss of 50.5 million rand a year earlier. Purple was unchanged
at 40 cents a share.  Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TKG SJ): Africa’s biggest fixed-
line operator appointed Pinky Moholi as chief executive officer.
The shares rose 25 cents, or 0.7 percent, to 35 rand.    Vunani Ltd. (VUN)  : The financial services company said
in a trading update it expects to report a per-share loss for
the year ended December to improve by at least 20 percent on the
13.2 cents-a-share loss it reported December 2009.  To contact the reporters on this story:
